data.Name: Very High
data.Description:
Refers to an attribute, property or quality assessed as being of an extremely elevated level, indicating a strong or intense presence. It emphasizes an extreme or exceptional level of the attribute. It can be used when underscoring that something is at the top end of the scale, indicating an extraordinary level. For example, very high temperatures, very high demand, or very high performance all suggest an exceptionally elevated level
(Recommended general usage: quantity or size)

data.Name: High
data.Description:
Refers to an attribute, property or quality assessed as indicating a level that is above average or elevated. It suggests a considerable degree or a position toward the upper end of a scale. For example, high temperatures, high demand, or high performance all suggest a level that is more than usual or expected
(Recommended general usage: quantity or size)

data.Name: Medium
data.Description:
Refers to an attribute, property or quality assessed as being of middle size, degree, or quality; an intermediate level. It implies something that falls in the middle range on a scale. Often used to describe size, intensity, or quantity. For example, a medium-sized shirt, medium heat, or medium difficulty suggests something that is neither large nor small, intense nor mild, difficult nor easy
(Recommended general usage: quantity or size)

data.Name: Low
data.Description:
Refers to an attribute, property or quality assessed as indicating a level that is below average or less than what is expected. It suggests a moderate degree or a position toward the lower end of a scale. For example, low temperatures, low income, or low performance all suggest a level that is less than usual or desired
(Recommended general usage: quantity or size)

data.Name: Very Low
data.Description:
Refers to an attribute, property or quality assessed as being at an extremely low level, suggesting a minimal or almost negligible presence. It can be used when underscoring that something is at the bottom end of the scale, indicating an extreme level of deficiency. For example, very low temperatures, very low income, or very low performance all suggest an exceptionally low level
(Recommended general usage: quantity or size)

data.Name: Excellent
data.Description:
Refers to an attribute, property or quality assessed as being of the highest quality or degree. Denotes a state of exceptional quality, surpassing the expected standard. It implies a high level of merit, superiority, or outstanding performance
(Recommended general usage: quality or desirability)

data.Name: Poor
data.Description:
Refers to an attribute, property or quality assessed as being below the expected standard, or not meeting a satisfactory level. It often implies a deficiency or inadequacy. It can be used to describe a condition, performance, quality, or state that falls short of what is considered acceptable or desirable
(Recommended general usage: quality or desirability)

data.Name: Good
data.Description:
Refers to an attribute, property or quality assessed as having positive qualities, quantity, or degree. It can be used to indicate a subjective judgment of positive quality or desirability
(Recommended general usage: quality or desirability)

data.Name: Satisfactory
data.Description:
Refers to an attribute, property or quality assessed as having satisfactory qualities, quantity, or degree. It can be used to indicate a subjective judgment of satisfactory quality or desirability
(Recommended general usage: quality or desirability)

data.Name: Very Strong
data.Description:
Refers to an attribute, property or quality assessed as having an extremely potent or exceptionally forceful presence. It suggests an outstanding high degree of strength, power, or effectiveness
(Recommended general usage: strength or intensity)

data.Name: Strong
data.Description:
Refers to an attribute, property or quality assessed as having a significant or powerful degree of the attribute, property or quality. Indicates a high degree of strength, power, or intensity
(Recommended general usage: strength or intensity)

data.Name: Moderate
data.Description:
Refers to an attribute, property or quality assessed as being kept within a certain limit; representing a balanced or average level. Average in intensity, amount, quality or degree for example: We walked at a moderate pace
(Recommended general usage: strength or intensity)

data.Name: Weak
data.Description:
Refers to an attribute, property or quality assessed as being below average in strength or intensity. Indicates a lack of strength, power, or intensity. Something described as weak is typically not robust, sturdy, or forceful. 
(Recommended general usage: strength or intensity)

data.Name: Very Weak
data.Description:
Refers to an attribute, property or quality assessed as being of an extremely low level of strength or intensity; it suggests a lack of strength, power, or intensity. It can be used to describe something that is notably deficient or feeble in terms of the specified quality
(Recommended general usage: strength or intensity)

data.Name: Confident
data.Description:
Describes the rated degree of confidence or certainty associated with a particular attribute or property, indicating a robust belief or assurance in the outcome of the interpretation. It implies that the existing evidence or information strongly substantiates the conclusion with a high level of confidence.
(Recommended general usage: confidence or certainty)

data.Name: Likely
data.Description:
Describes the rated degree of confidence or certainty associated with a particular attribute or property, indicating strong probability or confidence in the accuracy of the interpretation. It implies that the available evidence points significantly toward the conclusion being the most probable or reasonable explanation.
(Recommended general usage: confidence or certainty)

data.Name: Probable
data.Description:
Describes the rated degree of confidence or certainty associated with a particular attribute or property, indicating  a high likelihood or strong probability of the accuracy of the interpretation. It implies that, based on the available evidence or information, the conclusion is highly likely. It may carry  a slightly more formal or technical connotation. In some contexts, "probable" can imply a higher level of certainty than "likely"
(Recommended general usage: confidence or certainty)

data.Name: Possible
data.Description:
Describes the rated degree of confidence or certainty associated with a particular attribute or property, indicating there may be other plausible interpretations, and the available information might not be sufficient to make a definitive judgment. It's a term commonly used when there is some ambiguity or lack of conclusive evidence in a given situation
(Recommended general usage: confidence or certainty)

data.Name: Uncertain
data.Description:
Describes the rated degree of confidence or certainty associated with a particular attribute or property, indicating there may be a lack of confidence in the accuracy of the interpretation due to factors such as incomplete information, ambiguity, or the presence of multiple plausible explanations. It's a term used when there is a recognition of the limitations in reaching a firm and conclusive judgment
(Recommended general usage: confidence or certainty)

data.Name: Low Confidence
data.Description:
Describes the rated degree of confidence or certainty associated with a particular attribute or property, indicating a lack of strong assurance in the accuracy of the interpretation. It implies that the conclusion may be subject to change or revision based on additional information or a more thorough analysis.
(Recommended general usage: confidence or certainty)
